<p>Hello All,</p><p>For much of my career, full conventional war was something that received very little discussion as a possible phenomena. The collapse of the Soviet Union and the military dominance that the USA showed in Desert Storm (the First Iraq War), meant that any large scale conventional war would have to not involve the USA (if the USA was involved, it would be dramatically different). Really, for 30 years it meant that when it came to war, the focus was overwhelmingly on things such as Insurgency/Counter-Insurgency, Air-power and special forces, Information/Hybrid War, etc. The study and discussion of large-scale conventional war seemed to decline dramatically in universities, for instance, and was relegated to military colleges and a small number of think-tanks. However, if much of the world was not interested in conventional war, conventional war (to steal a line that has been reputedly said Leon Trotsky) was always interested in us.<a id="footnote-anchor-1" href="#footnote-1">1</a></p><figure><a href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6b96e392-d26a-4500-8668-00f3e34e8dbe_711x965.jpeg" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/SU66jGix9kNErfHKI0sHWs_ 424w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/_gPXKP46msFHiZpUFHCjjkZNV4WSDov5LE-xNL7xdlc=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd184NDgsY19saW1pdCxmX3dlYnAscV9hdXRvOmdvb2QsZmxfcHJvZ3Jlc3NpdmU6c3RlZXAvaHR0cHMlM0ElMkYlMkZzdWJzdGFjay1wb3N0LW1lZGlhLnMzLmFtYXpvbmF3cy5jb20lMkZwdWJsaWMlMkZpbWFnZXMlMkY2Yjk2ZTM5Mi1kMjZhLTQ1MDAtODY2OC0wMGYzZTM0ZThkYmVfNzExeDk2NS5qcGVn 848w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/I7EglmAmQTt_JPAKschad8N9buzjYXuxi5-ESR-ZDzM=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd18xMjcyLGNfbGltaXQsZl93ZWJwLHFfYXV0bzpnb29kLGZsX3Byb2dyZXNzaXZlOnN0ZWVwL2h0dHBzJTNBJTJGJTJGc3Vic3RhY2stcG9zdC1tZWRpYS5zMy5hbWF6b25hd3MuY29tJTJGcHVibGljJTJGaW1hZ2VzJTJGNmI5NmUzOTItZDI2YS00NTAwLTg2NjgtMDBmM2UzNGU4ZGJlXzcxMXg5NjUuanBlZw== 1272w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/q1wylO2YxUiroCnPgGe3RJSpA- 1456w" sizes="100vw"/><img src="https://reader.miniflux." width="711" height="965" alt="Leon Trotsky - Uicipeid" title="Leon Trotsky - Uicipeid" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/iMuIkxBfEZ6v-9aPDmR2xQVuE-LsQxPn_imTZg8B0k8=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd180MjQsY19saW1pdCxmX2F1dG8scV9hdXRvOmdvb2QsZmxfcHJvZ3Jlc3NpdmU6c3RlZXAvaHR0cHMlM0ElMkYlMkZzdWJzdGFjay1wb3N0LW1lZGlhLnMzLmFtYXpvbmF3cy5jb20lMkZwdWJsaWMlMkZpbWFnZXMlMkY2Yjk2ZTM5Mi1kMjZhLTQ1MDAtODY2OC0wMGYzZTM0ZThkYmVfNzExeDk2NS5qcGVn 424w, https://reader.miniflux. 848w, https://reader.miniflux. 1272w, https://reader.miniflux. 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"/></picture></a><figcaption>Leon Trotsky: Bolshevik Minister of War in the Russian Civil War, and mass murderer.</figcaption></figure><p>In the last few years, conventional war has returned with a vengeance. The Russian full-scale invasion of Ukraine figures most prominently, but also the Azerbaijani campaigns to retake Nagorno-Karabakh, and now what looks it will be an Israeli conventional campaign to occupy Gaza (more on that below). Moreover, its not just the actual conventional wars that threaten our world, there is a real possibility that the largest economic/technological powers in the world could go to war in the near future. China and India have competing claims on their border that regularly erupt into small-scale confrontation and, of course, the US and China are now openly confronting each other in the seas of the Indo-Pacific region.</p><figure><a href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F7f2b13da-a1c2-4393-abef-d3667938ad92_445x267.jpeg" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/FTAkZ3XGXUAIaKCqC-t9GoWkmJUbFmpjqPR3A_JESjE=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd180MjQsY19saW1pdCxmX3dlYnAscV9hdXRvOmdvb2QsZmxfcHJvZ3Jlc3NpdmU6c3RlZXAvaHR0cHMlM0ElMkYlMkZzdWJzdGFjay1wb3N0LW1lZGlhLnMzLmFtYXpvbmF3cy5jb20lMkZwdWJsaWMlMkZpbWFnZXMlMkY3ZjJiMTNkYS1hMWMyLTQzOTMtYWJlZi1kMzY2NzkzOGFkOTJfNDQ1eDI2Ny5qcGVn 424w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/8Qq0aNLNq24kWINWwMs6yjjppAlc-DgHrqETmPjFaJY=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd184NDgsY19saW1pdCxmX3dlYnAscV9hdXRvOmdvb2QsZmxfcHJvZ3Jlc3NpdmU6c3RlZXAvaHR0cHMlM0ElMkYlMkZzdWJzdGFjay1wb3N0LW1lZGlhLnMzLmFtYXpvbmF3cy5jb20lMkZwdWJsaWMlMkZpbWFnZXMlMkY3ZjJiMTNkYS1hMWMyLTQzOTMtYWJlZi1kMzY2NzkzOGFkOTJfNDQ1eDI2Ny5qcGVn 848w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/b0GCWVvDUcHuPg-ICsw9Wll2vLIL5V6D1m5eY-LQrLw=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd18xMjcyLGNfbGltaXQsZl93ZWJwLHFfYXV0bzpnb29kLGZsX3Byb2dyZXNzaXZlOnN0ZWVwL2h0dHBzJTNBJTJGJTJGc3Vic3RhY2stcG9zdC1tZWRpYS5zMy5hbWF6b25hd3MuY29tJTJGcHVibGljJTJGaW1hZ2VzJTJGN2YyYjEzZGEtYTFjMi00MzkzLWFiZWYtZDM2Njc5MzhhZDkyXzQ0NXgyNjcuanBlZw== 1272w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/nXq5Od4kQeKHDbpEycVwcNBkXZ6EXBl-VqQDICCTGIw=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd18xNDU2LGNfbGltaXQsZl93ZWJwLHFfYXV0bzpnb29kLGZsX3Byb2dyZXNzaXZlOnN0ZWVwL2h0dHBzJTNBJTJGJTJGc3Vic3RhY2stcG9zdC1tZWRpYS5zMy5hbWF6b25hd3MuY29tJTJGcHVibGljJTJGaW1hZ2VzJTJGN2YyYjEzZGEtYTFjMi00MzkzLWFiZWYtZDM2Njc5MzhhZDkyXzQ0NXgyNjcuanBlZw== 1456w" sizes="100vw"/><img src="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/7Jxhmm9fjCha2YnFczw-y_" width="445" height="267" alt="Indian anger and Chinese indifference quash hopes of border resolution |  India | The Guardian" title="Indian anger and Chinese indifference quash hopes of border resolution |  India | The Guardian" srcset="https://reader.miniflux. 424w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/RJ6IwESrGJnAxsWcA7XNsS6OBLx-PL6LI38DzcjPLBo=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd184NDgsY19saW1pdCxmX2F1dG8scV9hdXRvOmdvb2QsZmxfcHJvZ3Jlc3NpdmU6c3RlZXAvaHR0cHMlM0ElMkYlMkZzdWJzdGFjay1wb3N0LW1lZGlhLnMzLmFtYXpvbmF3cy5jb20lMkZwdWJsaWMlMkZpbWFnZXMlMkY3ZjJiMTNkYS1hMWMyLTQzOTMtYWJlZi1kMzY2NzkzOGFkOTJfNDQ1eDI2Ny5qcGVn 848w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/pGXBnYgp430rTXwgLjLWQx41G8MLT7-Rcq0xffBmjXY=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd18xMjcyLGNfbGltaXQsZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0bzpnb29kLGZsX3Byb2dyZXNzaXZlOnN0ZWVwL2h0dHBzJTNBJTJGJTJGc3Vic3RhY2stcG9zdC1tZWRpYS5zMy5hbWF6b25hd3MuY29tJTJGcHVibGljJTJGaW1hZ2VzJTJGN2YyYjEzZGEtYTFjMi00MzkzLWFiZWYtZDM2Njc5MzhhZDkyXzQ0NXgyNjcuanBlZw== 1272w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/7Jxhmm9fjCha2YnFczw-y_ 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"/></picture></a><figcaption>Indian and Chinese forces clash on their common border, April 2023: https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/apr/28/india-accuses-china-of-aggressions-amid-border-stalemate</figcaption></figure><p>The return of conventional war is perhaps the single most important strategic development of this era, and its one that we must try to understand, prepare for (and ultimately try and prevent). One of the key elements in that, is to make people understand that the choice for conventional war is almost always catastrophic for the state that initiates the war. One of the most distressing things about the discussion of a Russian invasion of Ukraine before Feb 24, 2022 was the widespread idea that such a war could be conventionally won quickly (one analyst even said confidently that the war would conventionally be over in a day or so). </p><p>Whatever happens, going forward, we need to study conventional war more closely. There is a good chance that it will define the era we are in and the one we are going into. With the US sure to experience a relative economic decline as the global south continues to grow, and democracy increasingly under threat, the chance of large-scale conventional war is almost certainly on the up. One of the reasons I was so pleased to join the Center for Strategic and International Studies as a Senior Associate (non-residential) this week is that it provides an ideal situation in which to contribute to what I see as fundamentally important work on war and power.<a id="footnote-anchor-2" href="#footnote-2">2</a> We have to hope that wars continuing interest in us is matched by a better understanding by us in what matters in war, and as such we can make conventional war less likely and not more.</p><p></p><p>Phillips’s Newsletter is a reader-supported publication. To receive new posts and support my work, consider becoming a free or paid subscriber.</p><p><strong>The Middle East and the Russo-Ukraine War</strong></p><p>Almost immediately after the Hamas attacks on Israel started yesterday morning, I started getting enquiries from the press for comments. I did not give any because I’m no expert in the region and nothing I can say would be of any value at all. And I certainly wont write much about it in the coming weeks. However, I was asked, quite interestingly, to think about what this might matter for Ukraine and the Russo-Ukraine War. Short answer now, is that is might matter hardly at all, or it could end up hardening different strategic groupings. </p><figure><a href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa22c054b-3e10-4edb-8c01-05d447321e7e_4234x2823.jpeg" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/nEZNvMuseCvJi79Wu86jlTf9rz25gUdWK9g00p_D2_4=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd180MjQsY19saW1pdCxmX3dlYnAscV9hdXRvOmdvb2QsZmxfcHJvZ3Jlc3NpdmU6c3RlZXAvaHR0cHMlM0ElMkYlMkZzdWJzdGFjay1wb3N0LW1lZGlhLnMzLmFtYXpvbmF3cy5jb20lMkZwdWJsaWMlMkZpbWFnZXMlMkZhMjJjMDU0Yi0zZTEwLTRlZGItOGMwMS0wNWQ0NDczMjFlN2VfNDIzNHgyODIzLmpwZWc= 424w, https://reader.miniflux. 848w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/98bm-pHTFFuxaHCpzpz8gt05F_VOs0AbYa05yx_ZMsA=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd18xMjcyLGNfbGltaXQsZl93ZWJwLHFfYXV0bzpnb29kLGZsX3Byb2dyZXNzaXZlOnN0ZWVwL2h0dHBzJTNBJTJGJTJGc3Vic3RhY2stcG9zdC1tZWRpYS5zMy5hbWF6b25hd3MuY29tJTJGcHVibGljJTJGaW1hZ2VzJTJGYTIyYzA1NGItM2UxMC00ZWRiLThjMDEtMDVkNDQ3MzIxZTdlXzQyMzR4MjgyMy5qcGVn 1272w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/i8vXC_xu2W5JbVuyJyCkqLsHe- 1456w" sizes="100vw"/><img src="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/RvPBfJZ9fTnPt3Jm_" alt="In photos: Hamas unleashes attack from Gaza on Israel - The Washington Post" title="In photos: Hamas unleashes attack from Gaza on Israel - The Washington Post" srcset="https://reader.miniflux. 424w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/2ZYY4RESyLlor1-5MJaGHZW7s- 848w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/B2CSIvZpwYLFMP6SfH_ 1272w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/RvPBfJZ9fTnPt3Jm_ 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"/></picture></a><figcaption>Hamas Rockets Fired towards Israel Yesterday</figcaption></figure><p>In the first instance. there might be very little impact on the Russo-Ukraine War. We need to be careful not to say that these attacks will spiral out of control. Israel may concentrate solely on trying to attack Hamas in Gaza, and limit the conflict in that way. In such an instance the impact on Ukraine would be minor. Could be a minor problem (more competition for ammunition supplies) combined with a minor positive (undermines the Republican Party narrative about isolationism—interesting to see the bipartisan reaction in the US to provide military equipment to Israel).</p><p>On the other hand, there is a chance that this does start leading to greater ‘bloc’ behavior and this will lead to more internationalizing of the Russo-Ukraine War. People who know far more about this conflict than I are saying that Iran almost certainly provided a great deal of the logistical and planning support needed by Hamas to launch such a well-planned and supplied operation. It would make sense—this would be almost impossible for Hamas to have resourced on its own. And this could matter, if in essence countries like Israel, which have sat on the fence in the Russo-Ukraine War, now start acting more and more as allies to one side or the other.</p><p>Certainly its interesting to see the instinctive reactions of Russia and Ukraine. President Zelensky released a strong statement in support of Israel, while the Russian Foreign Ministry released a statement that supported the Palestinian position on territorial return. </p><p>Here is Zelensky’s statement:</p><p><em>“Today, the entire world saw horrifying videos from Israel. Terrorists humiliate women and men, detain even the elderly, and show no mercy,” Zelensky’s <a href="https://twitter.com/ZelenskyyUa/status/1710723464414282183" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">post</a> read. “In the face of such a terrorist strike, everyone who values life must stand in solidarity.”</em></p><p><em>“We in Ukraine have a special feeling about what has happened. Thousands of rockets in the Israeli sky… People killed just on the streets… Civilian cars shot through… Detainees being humiliated…,” Zelensky continued. “Our position is crystal clear: anyone who causes terror and death anywhere on the planet must be held accountable. Today’s terrorist attack on Israel was well-planned, and the entire world knows which sponsors of terrorism could have endorsed and enabled its organization.”</em><a id="footnote-anchor-3" href="#footnote-3">3</a></p><p>Here is the Russian Foreign Ministry statement:</p><p><em>Russia is gravely concerned over a sharp escalation of the Palestinian-Israeli conflict. In this we regard we would like to reaffirm our principled and consistent stance that this conflict, which has continued for 75 years, cannot be resolved by force and can be settled exclusively by political and diplomatic means, by engaging in a full-fledged negotiation process based on the well-known international legal framework stipulating the establishment of an independent Palestinian state within the 1967 borders with a capital in East Jerusalem that co-exists with Israel in peace and security.</em><a id="footnote-anchor-4" href="#footnote-4">4</a></p><p>Now actually until this time, many states such as Israel have tried not to join one-side or the other in the Russo-Ukraine War. They have deliberately provided only limited support to Ukraine and tried to keep good relations with Russia. This may no longer be possible—especially if Israel broadens its response to include attacks far from Gaza. There are already official Israeli statements that they are attacking targets in Lebanon. However the most dramatic broadening would be Israeli attacks on targets in Iran. Iran is arguably Russia’s most important strategic ally in the war, having provided Russia with absolutely vital military aid, most famously the Shahed UAVs, which Iran is helping Russia to mass-produce. </p><figure><a href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F5c0784f0-8cda-4c2f-8878-015dbd68fa88_770x770.png" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/yvH6AOwPq5UI99yBakXtG8wNIW0_Rdn_PeC0WQkr0Eo=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd180MjQsY19saW1pdCxmX3dlYnAscV9hdXRvOmdvb2QsZmxfcHJvZ3Jlc3NpdmU6c3RlZXAvaHR0cHMlM0ElMkYlMkZzdWJzdGFjay1wb3N0LW1lZGlhLnMzLmFtYXpvbmF3cy5jb20lMkZwdWJsaWMlMkZpbWFnZXMlMkY1YzA3ODRmMC04Y2RhLTRjMmYtODg3OC0wMTVkYmQ2OGZhODhfNzcweDc3MC5wbmc= 424w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/- 848w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/v7_Cn3FSp9LmP2xTyoQjPd- 1272w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/ipabsmx1nd9r6Q_O0abnW3BUgCJPHmsgjF_l4NQyL4E=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd18xNDU2LGNfbGltaXQsZl93ZWJwLHFfYXV0bzpnb29kLGZsX3Byb2dyZXNzaXZlOnN0ZWVwL2h0dHBzJTNBJTJGJTJGc3Vic3RhY2s